The Rochester City School District is providing meals to students at 20 school locations throughout the City of Rochester starting today while students begin the school year under a remote learning model on Monday, September 14. Grab-and-go breakfast and lunch will be served to RCSD students between 10 a.m. and 2:00 p.m., Monday through Friday. The list of 20 meal sites is located on the District website at www.rcsdk12.org/meals.

El Distrito Escolar de la Ciudad de Rochester ofrecerá comidas a los estudiantes en 20 escuelas de toda la ciudad de Rochester a partir de hoy, al mismo tiempo que los estudiantes comienzan el año escolar bajo un modelo de aprendizaje a distancia el lunes 14 de septiembre. Se servirá desayuno y almuerzo a Estudiantes del Distrito para llevar entre las 10 am y las 2:00 pm, de lunes a viernes. La lista de los 20 sitios de distribución de comidas se encuentra en el sitio web del Distrito en www.rcsdk12.org/meals, marque en la pestaña de recursos familiares y sitios de distribución de comidas. Gracias!

post_text:
The Rochester City School District Board of Education is pleased announce the appointment of Kallia Wade as District Clerk and Special Assistant to the Board of Education, effective September 1, 2020.

Ms. Wade has worked closely with the Board in several capacities, serving as Community Liaison Specialist since 2017.

Prior to joining the District, Wade worked with the District’s young adults through the University of Rochester’s Teen Health and Success Partnership Program, a collaboration with Hillside Work Scholarship. Prior to this, Ms. Wade spent several years working in the English as a Second Language (ESL) Education industry with Kaplan International Colleges in both Whittier and Berkeley, California.

Ms. Wade earned her Master’s Degree in Education Policy from University of Rochester’s Warner School and earned a Bachelor of Arts Degree in English and Child Development at Whittier College in Whittier, California.

Prior to this, Ms. Wade spent several years working in the English as a Second Language (ESL) Education industry with Kaplan International Colleges in both Whittier and Berkeley, California.

This is the third of five virtual parent sessions on the District’s Reopening Plan for the 2020-21 school year. The meeting was held on Augusut 19, 2020 via YouTube.

Please note: This Parent Forum begins at 1 minute 45 seconds into the video.

All Parent sessions will focus on certain components of our reopening plan and how learning will take place. Please join the District leadership for sessions beginning on Saturday, August 15 through Friday, August 21.

Parents, students, and community members who are interested in submitting questions for a remaining meeting may do so during or in advance of any meeting by emailing reopening@rcsdk12.org.

To learn more about specific session times, view the District’s plan, or to view a school-specific plan, please visit www.rcsdk12.org/reopens or call the RCSD Support Hotline at 585-262-8700.

post_text:
Dear Families,

Last week, the Rochester City School District announced that all students will begin the school year in September under a remote learning model for the first ten weeks of school. Tuesday, August 18, the RCSD will host the 2nd of five virtual parent sessions starting at 10 a.m. that will focus on the District’s reopening plan and how learning will take place.

This meeting will be conducted via You Tube, and we encourage you to go to our website at https://www.rcsdk12.org/reopeningforums for links to each live stream meeting. post_text:
Today Governor Cuomo announced that levels of COVID-19 are low enough to open schools in New York State. In addition, the Governor is requiring districts to do the following:

• Post their remote learning, testing, and contact tracing plans online
• Schedule five discussion sessions with parents and caregivers before August 21
• Schedule a discussion session with staff before August 21

These specific components of our plan will be readily accessible to all stakeholders no later than August 21, as outlined by the Governor, via our dedicated reopening website at www.rcsdk12.org/reopens. Also, our COVID-19 Reopening team will review our school and District plans to determine if any changes need to be made.

While this has been one of the most challenging times for our students, parents, and staff, we are committed to ensuring that high-quality learning takes place for all students in a fair and equitable way.

post_text:
To help promote the achievement of boys of color, the RCSD is collaborating with the City of Rochester, My Brother's Keeper Initiative, and a number of community organizations to offer a unique networking opportunity.

Organizations such as Healthi Kids, Healthy Baby Network, and North Star Rites of Passage will offer learning resources, legal information, and other support that will help remove barriers so men in our community can better assist students to achieve academic success.

Studies show that when a father is involved in a student’s life, that child does better academically and has a greater opportunity to graduate, go on to college, and develop the skills necessary for a successful career.

Please provide in the subject line “Rochester State Monitor Public Meeting” and include in the email your name, position (e.g., parent, teacher, district resident), and any information you want to be part of the record of the public hearing. Please note the deadline to register to speak at the public hearing is 12:00 p.m. the day of the public hearing. For more information, please visit www.rcsdk12.org/statemonitorhearings

RCSDK12.ORG
State Monitor Public Hearings / State Monitor Public Hearings

We are writing to let you know that starting July 1, 2020, the RCSDlink app will be discontinued. In September, the District will begin using the PowerSchool portal and app. PowerSchool offers a web portal and a mobile application that will display student data and attendance in real-time.

Look for a mailing in late August, where you will receive login credentials to access PowerSchool. To ensure you receive your login credentials, please contact your child’s school to update your address, phone number, and email.

To learn more about the new PowerSchool portal, please visit www.rcsdk12.org/parentportal.

This is a message for all Rochester City School District Families. Summer Meals are here! They’re free and available at safe drop-in locations all over the city, where you can stop in and pick up meals to bring home to your children, ages 2-18. If you’ve already been picking up meals from a school or community site, those sites are continuing to serve. If you haven’t yet, you can dial 2-1-1 or visit http://ow.ly/CXug50AhGfM to find a time and location near you.

As a reminder, there are some changes in bell times that will affect several schools next school year. If you haven’t done so already, please visit the District website at http://ow.ly/H4US50AhGfN to view the updated bell times.

Thank you for everything you are doing to support your children during these challenging times.

The last day of instruction for all students and teachers in the RCSD will be Friday, June 19. Thank you for your steadfast commitment to our students and families, especially during these past 12 weeks. I truly appreciate all of your time, continued efforts, and hard work.

post_text: Nasmil Campusano (right), and her sister Jazmin celebrated Nasmil’s upcoming graduation from the Bilingual Language and Literacy Academy. Nasmil’s teachers delivered a cap and gown to her today along with graduation signs honoring her accomplishment. Nasmil and Jazmin were born conjoined twins. A team of surgeons, anesthesiologists, and surgical nurses performed a 7 and-a-half hour surgery in January of 2000 to separate the two.

post_text: Today, Governor Cuomo announced that all schools in New York State will remain closed for the rest of this school year. The District will continue to support our students and families during this extended closure. Monday, May 4, is a previously scheduled Superintendent’s Conference Day, with no school for students, so teachers may not be connecting with students that day. Third-quarter report cards will be mailed home next week. Please continue to visit our website at www.rcsdk12.org/covid19 for updates, as well as educational resources. Families are encouraged to call the District’s support hotline at 262-8700 for assistance.

post_text:
Congratulations to Zechariah Harris-Scott, Damani Barley, and Shariona Blocker from East High School, Maurice McKinney from Leadership Academy for Young Men, India Jordan and Carrington Hayward from School of the Arts, Aidan Delehanty and Jaden Connolly from World of Inquiry, and Jahkier Moore from Joseph C. Wilson Magnet High School. All of these student athletes were All-Greater Rochester Winter 2020 selections by the Democrat and Chronicle. Harris-Scott, Barley, Blocker, McKinney, and Jordan were recognized for their efforts on the basketball court. Delehanty is a standout in boys swimming, Moore was recognized for his efforts in track and field, and Connolly and Hayward are standout bowlers. Congratulations to all of these wonderful student athletes. You are excellent RCSD role models!

https://www.democratandchronicle.com/storytelling/storystack/agr-all-greater-rochester-winter-2020-main-page-basketball-hockey-swimming-wrestling-skiing-bowling-track-zoom/

post_text: The RCSD is deeply saddened by the loss of Suzanne Johnston. She passed away suddenly over the weekend. Johnston served as Principal of Wilson Magnet High School where she welcomed President George H. Bush in 1989. After working for the RCSD, Johnston served as President of Our Lady of Mercy School for Young Women. She also worked in the West Irondequoit School District. The RCSD sends its condolences to Johnston’s family.
shared_text:
Adam Chodak
April 8 at 12:05 AM ·

"I do think that if you're going to have any trust, if you mess up, you better fess up." - Suzanne Johnston

Sue passed away suddenly this week. She was role model and mentor to students and staff alike at Rochester City School District's Wilson Magnet HS and Our Lady of Mercy School for Young Women.

Here's her talking with Marlowe Washington and me about leadership as part of News 8 WROC Rochester's special broadcast on race...

post_text:
Joint Statement from Board of Education President Van Henri White and Superintendent Terry J. Dade.

We are extremely grateful to Governor Cuomo and our local delegation for securing the $35-million-dollars we need for the remainder of this school year. This is a huge financial boost to ensure we finish this school year without an additional deficit moving into the 2020 – 2021 school year. We all understand these are tough fiscal times, but this big yes from the Governor and state lawmakers, and the addition of a monitor, will go a long way to begin our fiscal stability moving forward.

The following is a message to parents from the New York State Office of Children and Family Services (OCFS).

If you are a parent or caregiver who needs child care, please complete this parent need for child care survey. Based on the information you provide about your job, employer, number of children, and financial need, OCFS may be able to help you find the child program you need. It may be a challenge to find child care due to COVID-19 related program closures, however the staff at OCFS are trying their best to support families to find the high quality child care that they need.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/3HSNNYJ
shared_text:

Parent Need for Child Care
text:
The following is a message to parents from the New York State Office of Children and Family Services (OCFS).

If you are a parent or caregiver who needs child care, please complete this parent need for child care survey. Based on the information you provide about your job, employer, number of children, and financial need, OCFS may be able to help you find the child program you need. It may be a challenge to find child care due to COVID-19 related program closures, however the staff at OCFS are trying their best to support families to find the high quality child care that they need.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/3HSNNYJ

SURVEYMONKEY.COM
Parent Need for Child Care

Thank you to all who attended this morning’s 4th Annual OACES Community Outreach Breakfast. The Office of Adult and Career Education Services (OACES), is a division of the Rochester City School District. This morning’s breakfast was an opportunity for OACES to showcase Adult Basic Education, Workforce Development, and Literacy Education Programs.

OACES is a workforce preparation organization that assists adult learners with a comprehensive range of career-related services that focus on transition to employment, advanced training, and post-secondary education. Available throughout the year, OACES programs and classes provide continuing education and career training and two large-scale, grant-funded immigrant and refugee resettlement projects. This mission of OACES is to build an active, employed, educated, and healthy Rochester community by providing open access to education and training opportunities through leveraged community resources.

post_text: Students from Edison Career and Technology High School are volunteering with Habitat for Humanity to build homes in the Rochester area. In the month of February, the District is celebrating Career and Technical Education Month to raise awareness of the role that CTE has in readying students for careers and college. On Wednesday, students spent the day working on two homes on Holloway Street in Rochester. Students from the construction pathway at Edison worked on maintenance, finishing drywall, painting, and installing ceramic tile. These are all types of skills the students have already learned in their construction pathway at Edison. #CTEMonth

post_text:
Thank you to everyone who spent time reading to students this morning at John James Audubon School No. 33 as part of World Read Aloud Day. Superintendent Terry Dade, Deputy Superintendent Lynda Quick, and several members of the community celebrated the day which is designed to promote literacy and the awareness that everyone has an inherit right to learn to read. World Read Aloud Day is celebrated globally by students, their schools, and proponents of literacy in more than 100 countries. Thank you to City Councilman Mitch Gruber, Rochester NY Police Department Chief La’Ron Singletary, Monroe County Executive Adam Bello, Monroe County District Attorney Sandra Doorley, Monroe County Sheriff's Office, Sheriff Todd Baxter, recruits from the MCSO's Court Bureau, News 8 WROC Rochester Maureen McGuire, WHEC TV Stacey Pensgen, along with staff and parents from School No. 33. To see more from today's World Read Aloud Day, please click on this link.

https://www.rcsdk12.org/worldreadaloud33
